\f0\fs28 \cf0 MEMO: Court Auditor\
RE: COMPAS Replacement Model\
\
To Whom it May Concern,\
\
This memo serves to outline the behavior of the COMPAS Replacement Model, limitations of the methods, and recommended further monitoring.\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 1. \ul Behavior of the Model
\f0\b0 \ulnone \
The model relies heavily on an individual\'92s prior criminal history. However, some other factors outside the individual\'92s control have significant influence: younger defendants are consistently scored higher, and race has a measurable influence. 
\f2\i \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 SHapley Additive exPlanations 
\f0\i0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 (SHAP) indicate repeatable and reliable patterns across similar individuals. 
\f2\i \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Local Interpretable Model\uc0\u8209 agnostic Explanations
\f0\i0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0  (LIME) indicate that some factors are case-specific and differ from person to person. Some of the predictions of the model are sensitive to small changes in the inputs, and the behavior of the model is very different among different demographic subgroups. Because of this, two individuals whose factors are nearly identical can have very different predicted scores. \
\

\f1\b 2. \ul Limitations of the Methods
\f0\b0 \ulnone \
Both SHAP and LIME methods rely heavily on how the data is preprocessed and encoded. SHAP assumes the model behaves similarly in similar cases; LIME may provide different output each time due to local sampling. \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Both methods may miss some of the complex interactions the model has learned.\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0  
\f2\i \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Diverse Counterfactual Explanations
\f3\b  
\f0\i0\b0 (DiCE) can provide recommendations for an individual to obtain a different predicted score, but cannot determine whether those recommended changes are ethically or legally justified. These methods reveal how the model behaves, not whether it should be allowed to behave in that manner.\
